{"title_page": "List of communist parties", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article about communist parties}}\n{{list to table|date=November 2019}}\n{{communism sidebar|by region}}\n{|{{Table|class=floatright}}\n|{{Graph:Map|scale=80|AF=#FF7F50|AL=#FF7F50|AM=#FF7F50|AO=#FF7F50|AR=#FF6347|AT=#FFA500|AZ=#FF7F50|BD=#FF6347|BG=#FFD700|BJ=#FF7F50|BR=#FFD700|BY=#FF7F50|CG=#FF7F50|CL=#FFD700|CN=#FF4500|CU=#FF4500|CY=#FFA500|CZ=#FF6347|DD=#FF7F50|EE=#FF7F50|ES=#FF6347|ET=#FF7F50|FI=#FFD700|FR=#FFD700|GD=#FF7F50|GE=#FF7F50|GR=#FF7F50|GY=#FFA500|HR=#FF7F50|HU=#FF7F50|IN=#FFD700|IT=#FFD700|KG=#FF7F50|KH=#FF7F50|KP=#FF4500|KZ=#FF7F50|LA=#FF4500|LK=#FFD700|LT=#FF7F50|LV=#FF7F50|MD=#FF7F50|ML=#FFD700|MN=#FF7F50|MZ=#FF7F50|NP=#FFA500|PA=#FF6347|PE=#FFD700|PL=#FF7F50|PT=#FF6347|RO=#FF7F50|RS=#FF6347|RU=#FF7F50|SM=#FFD700|SO=#FF7F50|SU=#FF7F50|SY=#FF6347|TJ=#FF7F50|TM=#FF7F50|UA=#FF7F50|UY=#FF6347|UZ=#FF7F50|VN=#FF4500|VZ=#FF6347|YD=#FF7F50|YU=#FF7F50|ZA=#FF6347}}\n|-\n|{{Legend0|OrangeRed|Officially ruling parties in communist states}}<br>{{Legend0|Tomato|Communist parties as ruling parties or part of a governing coalition in multi-party states}}<br>{{Legend0|Coral|Formerly ruling in a one-party system}}<br>{{Legend0|Orange|Formerly ruling in a parliamentary majority or minority government}}<br>{{Legend0|Gold|Formerly ruling as a coalition partner or supporter}}\n|}\nThere are a number of [[communist parties]] active in various countries across the world and a number that used to be active. They differ not only in method, but also in strict ideology and interpretation, although they are generally within the [[Marxist]] [[communism]] tradition.\n\nThe formation of communist parties in various countries was first initiated by the Russian [[Bolsheviks]] within the [[Communist International]]. Since then, communist parties have governed numerous countries, whether as ruling parties in [[one-party states]] like the [[Communist Party of China]] or the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]], or as ruling parties in [[multi-party system]]s, including majority and minority governments as well as leading or being part of several coalitions.\n\nMany other communist parties did not govern any country, but they did govern several states or region within a particular countries. Others have also been represented in the national, state or regional [[parliament]]s. Some communist parties and [[List of communist ideologies|schools of thought]] reject [[Parliamentarism|parliamentary representation]] and advocate [[insurrection]] or [[social revolution]].\n\n== Officially ruling in communist states ==\nIn the following countries, several communist parties either lead the ruling coalition or hold monopoly on state power as defined by their respective country's constitutions.\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|China}}{{efn|[[Hong Kong]] and [[Macau]] are administrated under the \"[[One country, two systems]]\" principle.}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of China]] leads the [[United Front (People's Republic of China)|United Front]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Cuba}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Cuba]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|North Korea}}{{efn|The [[Workers' Party of Korea]] is considered by some scholars to not be a communist party. <ref>{{cite book|title=Ethnic Nationalism in Korea: Genealogy, Politics, and Legacy|last=Shin|first=Gi-wook|publisher=[[Stanford University Press]]|year=2006|isbn=9780804754088}}</ref> While recently it started to consider itself as [[Juche]]ist exclusively, the party nonetheless participates in the [[International Meeting of Communist and Workers' Parties]].<ref>[http://www.solidnet.org/15-imcwp/15-imcwp-list-of-participants \"List of participants of 15th International Meeting of Communist and Workers'\"]. Solidnet. {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224034053/http://www.solidnet.org/15-imcwp/15-imcwp-list-of-participants|date=24 December 2013}}. Retrieved 24 December 2013.</ref>}} \u2013 [[Workers' Party of Korea]] leads the [[Democratic Front for the Reunification of the Fatherland]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Laos}} \u2013 [[Lao People's Revolutionary Party]] leads the [[Lao Front for National Construction]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Vietnam}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Vietnam]] leads the [[Vietnamese Fatherland Front]]\n\n== Ruling or part of ruling coalition in multi-party states ==\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Argentina}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Argentina]] and [[Communist Party of Argentina (Extraordinary Congress)]] participate in the [[Frente de Todos (2019 coalition)|ruling coalition]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bangladesh}} \u2013 [[Workers Party of Bangladesh]] participates in the [[Grand Alliance (Bangladesh)|ruling coalition]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Belarus}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Belarus]] supports the government of president [[Alexander Lukashenko]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Czech Republic}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia]] supports the government of [[ANO 2011]] and the [[Czech Social Democratic Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Nepal}} \u2013 [[Nepal Communist Party]] was formed as the merger of [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist Centre)]] and [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist\u2013Leninist)]] \n* {{flag+link|Politics of|Palestine|name=Palestine}} \u2013 [[Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine]] and [[Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine]] participates in the [[Palestinian Legislative Council|ruling coalition]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Serbia}} \u2013 [[Communist Party (Serbia)|Communist Party]] participates in the [[Serbian Progressive Party]]\u2013[[Socialist Party of Serbia]] coalition government.\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|South Africa}} \u2013 [[South African Communist Party]] participates in the [[African National Congress|ruling coalition]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Spain}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Spain]] participates in the [[S\u00e1nchez II Government|ruling coalition]] as part of the [[United Left (Spain)|United Left]] alliance\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Syria}} \u2013 [[Syrian Communist Party (Bakdash)|Syrian Communist Party]] and [[Syrian Communist Party (Unified)]] participate in the [[National Progressive Front (Syria)|ruling coalition]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Venezuela}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Venezuela]] and [[Tupamaro (Venezuela)|Tupamaro]] participate in the [[Great Patriotic Pole|ruling coalition]]\n\n== Formerly ruling ==\n=== One-party system ===\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Afghanistan|1980}} ([[Democratic Republic of Afghanistan|1978\u20131992]]) \u2013 [[People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan]] abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Albania|1946}} ([[People's Socialist Republic of Albania|1946\u20131992]]) \u2013 [[Party of Labour of Albania]] (known from 1941 to 1948 as the Communist Party of Albania) abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]] and is now known as [[Socialist Party of Albania]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Angola|1975}} ([[People's Republic of Angola|1975\u20131992]]) \u2013 [[MPLA|Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola \u2013 Labour Party]] (known from 1956 to 1977 as Popular Movement for the Liberation of Angola) abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Benin|1975}} ([[People's Republic of Benin|1975\u20131990]]) \u2013 [[People's Revolutionary Party of Benin]] abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]] and is now known as [[Union of Forces of Progress (Benin)|Union of Forces of Progress]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bulgaria|1946}} ([[People's Republic of Bulgaria|1946\u20131990]]) \u2013 [[Bulgarian Communist Party]], known from 1938\u20131948 as Bulgarian Workers' Party (Communists), abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] and is now known as [[Bulgarian Socialist Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Cambodia|1975}} ([[Democratic Kampuchea|1975\u20131979]], [[People's Republic of Kampuchea|1979\u20131992]]) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Kampuchea]], broke up into the exile, non-ruling and now defunct [[Party of Democratic Kampuchea]] and ruling [[Cambodian People's Party|Kampuchean People's Revolutionary Party]] which abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for centrism and is now known as [[Cambodian People's Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Congo-Brazzaville|1970}} ([[People's Republic of the Congo|1969\u20131992]]) \u2013 [[Congolese Party of Labour]] abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]]\n* {{flag+link|Politics of|Croatia|variant=SR Croatia}} ([[Socialist Republic of Croatia|1945\u20131990]]) \u2013 [[League of Communists of Croatia]] (known from 1937 to 1952 as the [[Communist Party of Croatia]]) abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] and [[Titoism]] for [[social democracy]] in 1989\u20131990 and is now known as [[Social Democratic Party of Croatia]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Czechoslovakia}} ([[Czechoslovak Socialist Republic|1948\u20131990]]) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Czechoslovakia]] broke up into the non-ruling [[Communist Party of Bohemia and Moravia]] and the [[Party of the Democratic Left (Slovakia)]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Ethiopia|1987}} ([[Derg|1974\u20131987]], ([[People's Democratic Republic of Ethiopia|1987\u20131991]]) \u2013 [[Commission for Organizing the Party of the Working People of Ethiopia]], [[Workers' Party of Ethiopia]]\n* {{flag+link|Politics of|East Germany}} (1949\u20131989) \u2013 [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany]] became [[Party of Democratic Socialism (Germany)|Party of Democratic Socialism]] and is now a part of [[The Left (Germany)|The Left]]\n* {{flag+link|Politics of|Greece|variant=Northern Greece|name=Northern Greece}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Greece]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Grenada}} ([[People's Revolutionary Government (Grenada)|1979\u20131983]]) \u2013 [[New Jewel Movement]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Hungary|1949}} ([[Hungarian Soviet Republic|1919]], [[Hungarian People's Republic|1949\u20131989]]) \u2013 [[Hungarian Communist Party]], [[Hungarian Working People's Party]], [[Hungarian Socialist Workers' Party]] abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]] and is now known as [[Hungarian Socialist Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Mongolia|1940}} ([[Mongolian People's Republic|1924\u20131992]]) \u2013 [[Mongolian People's Party|Mongolian People's Revolutionary Party]] (known from 1921 to 1924 and today too as the Mongolian People's Party) abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Mozambique|1975}} ([[People's Republic of Mozambique|1975\u20131990]]) \u2013 [[FRELIMO|Frelimo Party]] (known from 1962 to 1977 as the Mozambique Liberation Front) abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]] and [[Democratic socialism]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Poland}} ([[Polish People's Republic|1944\u20131989]]) \u2013 [[Polish Workers' Party]], [[Polish United Workers' Party]] abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]] and is now known as [[Democratic Left Alliance]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Romania|1965}} ([[Socialist Republic of Romania|1947\u20131989]]) \u2013 [[Romanian Communist Party]] dissolved after the [[Romanian Revolution]] (known from 1948 to 1965 as Romanian Workers' Party)\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Somalia}} ([[Somali Democratic Republic|1969\u20131991]]) \u2013 [[Supreme Revolutionary Council (Somalia)|Supreme Revolutionary Council]] (1969\u20131976), [[Somali Revolutionary Socialist Party]] (1976\u20131991)\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Soviet Union}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] (known from 1918 to 1925 as the Russian Communist Party (Bolsheviks) and from 1925 to 1952 as the All-Union Communist Party (Bolsheviks) (1917\u20131991)\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Turkmenistan}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Turkmenistan]] dissolved in December 1991\n* {{flag+link|Politics of|Yemen|variant=South Yemen}} (1967\u20131990) \u2013 [[Yemeni Socialist Party]] (known from 1963 to 1978 as [[National Liberation Front (Yemen)|National Liberation Front]]) abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]] for [[social democracy]]\n* {{flag+link|Politics of|Yugoslavia|variant=1945}} (1945\u20131990) \u2013 [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia]] (known from 1919 to 1952 as the [[Communist Party of Yugoslavia]]) in 1990 broken up into separate parties in each constituent republic (republics' parties existed before and the League of Communists of Yugoslavia was a federation of [[League of Communists of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[League of Communists of Croatia]], [[League of Communists of Macedonia]], [[League of Communists of Montenegro]], [[League of Communists of Serbia]] and [[League of Communists of Slovenia]]) which abandoned [[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]\u2013[[Titoism]] for [[social democracy]], the [[New Communist Party of Yugoslavia]] could be considered the ideological successor\n\n=== Parliamentary majority or minority government ===\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bangladesh}} (1975) \u2013 [[Bangladesh Krishak Sramik Awami League]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Chad}} (1993) - [[Chadian Action for Unity and Socialism]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Cyprus}} (2008\u20132013) \u2013 [[Progressive Party of Working People]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Guyana}} (1992\u20132015) \u2013 [[People's Progressive Party (Guyana)|People's Progressive Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Moldova}} (2001\u20132009) \u2013 [[Party of Communists of the Republic of Moldova]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Nepal}} (1994\u20131995, 2008\u20132013) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist\u2013Leninist)]] and [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist Centre)]], known from 1994 to 2009 as the [[Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist)]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Austria}} (1945\u20131949) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Austria]] participated in the provisional coalition of the [[Government of Austria]] after [[World War II]] and for four more years after the [[1945 Austrian legislative election]]\n\n=== Coalition partner or supporter ===\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Argentina}} (2003\u20132015) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Argentina]], in coalition governments with [[Front for Victory]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Brazil}} (2003\u20132016) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Brazil]], in coalition governments with [[Workers' Party (Brazil)|Workers' Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bulgaria}} (2005\u20132009, 2013\u20132014) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Bulgaria]], in coalition government as member of the [[Coalition for Bulgaria]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Chile}} (1937\u20131941, 1942\u20131946, 1970\u20131973, 2014\u20132018) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Chile]], in coalition governments as a member of the [[Popular Front (Chile)|Popular Front]], [[Democratic Alliance of Chile|Democratic Alliance]], [[Popular Unity (Chile)|Popular Unity]], and now [[New Majority (Chile)|New Majority]].\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|France}} (1981\u20131989; 1997\u20132002) \u2013 [[French Communist Party]] as a part of the [[Union of the Left (France)|Union de la gauche]] and of the [[Gauche plurielle]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Iran}} (1946) \u2013 [[Tudeh Party of Iran]], in the [[coalition government of Ahmad Qavam]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Abrahamian|first=Ervand|year=1982|url=https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/234|title=Iran Between Two Revolutions|publisher=Princeton University Press|pages=[https://archive.org/details/iranbetweentwore00abra_0/page/234 234\u2212237]|isbn=0-691-10134-5}}</ref>\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Italy}} (1976\u20131979, 2006\u20132008) \u2013 [[Italian Communist Party]] in [[Historic Compromise]] and [[Communist Refoundation Party]] in coalition government of [[The Union (Italy)|The Union]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Mali}} (2005\u20132014) \u2013 [[Malian Party of Labour]], participated in the [[Alliance for Democracy in Mali]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Norway}} (1945) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Norway]] in coalition government as member of [[Gerhardsen's First Cabinet]] lead by the [[Labour Party (Norway)|Labour Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Peru}} (2011\u20132016) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Peru]], in coalition governments as member of the [[Peru Wins]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Portugal}} (2015\u20132019) \u2013 [[Portuguese Communist Party]] in support of the [[XXI Constitutional Government of Portugal]] led by the [[Socialist Party (Portugal)|Socialist Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|San Marino}} (1945\u20131957, 1978\u20131992) \u2013 [[Sammarinese Communist Party]], in coalition government with [[Sammarinese Socialist Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Sri Lanka}} (1970\u20131975, 2004\u20132015) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Sri Lanka]], in coalition governments with the [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Finland}} (1944\u20131948, 1966\u20131970, 1970\u20131971, 1975\u20131976 and 1977\u20131982) \u2013 [[Finnish People's Democratic League]], in coalition governments with numerous other parties\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Uruguay}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Uruguay]] and [[People's Victory Party]], in coalition governments with the [[Broad Front (Uruguay)|Broad Front]]\n\n== Modern non-ruling ==\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Abkhazia}} (unrecognized country) \u2013 [[Communist Party of Abkhazia]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Afghanistan}} \u2013 [[Communist (Maoist) Party of Afghanistan]], [[Afghanistan Liberation Organization]], [[Marxist\u2013Leninist Organization of Afghanistan]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Albania}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Albania (1991)|Communist Party of Albania]], [[Communist Party of Albania 8 November]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Algeria}} \u2013 [[Algerian Party for Democracy and Socialism]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Angola}} \u2013 [[Party of the Angolan Communist Community]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Argentina}} \u2013 [[Revolutionary Communist Party of Argentina]], [[Liberation Party (Argentina)|Liberation Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Armenia}} \u2013 [[Armenian Communist Party]], [[United Communist Party of Armenia]], [[Progressive United Communist Party of Armenia]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Australia}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Australia (1971)|Communist Party of Australia]], [[Communist Party of Australia (Marxist\u2013Leninist)]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Austria}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Austria]], [[Party of Labour of Austria]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Azerbaijan}} \u2013 [[Azerbaijan Communist Party (1993)|Azerbaijan Communist Party]], [[Communist Party of Azerbaijan (1996)|Communist Party of Azerbaijan]] (1996), [[Communist Party of Azerbaijan (2011)|Communist Party of Azerbaijan]] (2011), [[United Communist Party of Azerbaijan]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bahrain}} \u2013 [[National Liberation Front \u2013 Bahrain]], [[Progressive Democratic Tribune]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bangladesh}} \u2013 [[Socialist Party of Bangladesh (Marxist)]], [[Communist Party of Bangladesh]], [[Socialist Party of Bangladesh]], [[Revolutionary Workers Party of Bangladesh]], [[Communist Party of Bangladesh (Marxist\u2013Leninist) (Dutta)|Communist Party of Bangladesh (Marxist\u2013Leninist)]] (Dutta), [[Communist Party of Bangladesh (Marxist\u2013Leninist) (Umar)|Communist Party of Bangladesh (Marxist\u2013Leninist)]] (Umar), [[Purba Banglar Sarbahara Party|Proletarian Party of East Bengal]], [[Maoist Bolshevik Reorganisation Movement of the Purba Banglar Sarbahara Party|Proletarian Party of East Bengal (Maoist Bolshevik Reorganisation Movement)]], [[Shramik Krishak Samajbadi Dal|Workers Peasants Socialist Party]], [[United Communist League of Bangladesh]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Belarus}} \u2013 [[Belarusian Left Party \"A Just World\"]], [[Communist Party of Belarus]], [[Group of Revolutionary Communists 'Red Wedge']], [[Communist Party of the Workers of Belarus]], [[Republican Committee of the Communist Party of Belarus]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Belgium}} \u2013 [[Workers' Party of Belgium]], [[Parti Communiste (Belgium)|Communist Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Benin}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Benin]], [[Marxist\u2013Leninist Communist Party of Benin]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bhutan}} \u2013 [[Bhutan Communist Party (Marxist\u2013Leninist\u2013Maoist)]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bolivia}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Bolivia]], [[People's Revolutionary Front (Marxist\u2212Leninist\u2212Maoist)]], [[Communist Party of Bolivia - Marxist Leninist Maoist]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bosnia and Herzegovina}} \u2013 [[Workers' Communist Party of Bosnia and Herzegovina]], [[Communist Party (Bosnia and Herzegovina)|Communist Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Botswana}} \u2013 [[MELS Movement Botswana|Marx, Engels, Lenin, Stalin Movement]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Brazil}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Brazil]], [[Brazilian Communist Party (1992)|Brazilian Communist Party]], [[Revolutionary Communist Party (Brazil)|Revolutionary Communist Party]], [[Free Homeland Party (Brazil)|Free Homeland Party]], [[Marxist\u2013Leninist Communist Party (Brazil)|Marxist\u2013Leninist Communist Party]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://inverta.org/pcml|title=Marxist\u2013Leninist Communist Party (Brazil)|publisher=Marxist\u2013Leninist Communist Party|accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Bulgaria}} \u2013 [[Bulgarian Communist Party(modern)|Bulgarian Communist Party]], [[Bulgarian Workers and Peasants Party]], [[Bulgarian Workers' Party/Communist/]], [[Bulgarian Workers Socialist Party]], [[Communist Party of Bulgaria]], [[Party of the Bulgarian Communists]], [[Resistance Movement \"23rd September\" Bulgaria]], [[Union of Communists in Bulgaria]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Burkina Faso}} \u2013 [[Party for Democracy and Socialism/Metba]], [[Voltaic Revolutionary Communist Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Burma}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Burma]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Canada}} \u2013 [[Communist Party of Canada]], [[Communist Party of Canada (Marxist\u2013Leninist)]], [[Revolutionary Communist Party of Canada]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|China}} \u2013 [[Maoist Communist Party of China]], [[Revolutionary Communist Party of China]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Taiwan}} \u2013 [[Labor Party (Taiwan)]], [[Taiwan Communist Party]], [[Communist Party of the Republic of China]], [[China Communist Alliance]], [[Taiwan Democratic Communist Party]]\n* {{flag+link|List of political parties in|Colombia}} \u2013 [[Colombian Communist Party]], [[Common Alternative Revolutionary Force]], [[Cl