{"title_page": "Rudi Dutschke", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Rudi Dutschke\n|image         = Rudi.jpg\n|image_size    =\n|alt           =\n|caption       =\n|birth_name    = Alfred Willi Rudi Dutschke\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1940|3|7|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Nuthe-Urstromtal|Sch\u00f6nefeld]], [[Gau March of Brandenburg|Brandenburg]], Germany\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1979|12|24|1940|3|7|df=yes}}\n|death_place   = [[\u00c5rhus]], Denmark\n|death_cause   = Drowning following [[epileptic seizure]]\n|known_for     = Spokesperson of the [[German student movement]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin]]\n|home_town     = [[Luckenwalde]], [[East Germany]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Gretchen Klotz|1966}}\n|children      = 3\n|footnotes     = }}\n'''Alfred Willi Rudolf \"Rudi\" Dutschke''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8\u0281u\u02d0di \u02c8d\u028at\u0283k\u0259|lang}}; 7 March 1940 \u2013 24 December 1979) was a German Marxist [[Sociology|sociologist]] and a political activist in the [[German student movement]], and the [[Au\u00dferparlamentarische Opposition|APO]] of the 1960s. \n\nHe advocated a \"[[long march through the institutions]] of power\" to create radical change from within government and society by becoming an integral part of the machinery.<ref name=\"Satya\">{{Citation | first = Richard | last = Huffmann | url = http://www.baader-meinhof.com/essays/SatyaEssay.html | publisher = Baader Meinhof | contribution = The Limits of Violence | title = Satya | date = March 2004 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081111192512/http://www.baader-meinhof.com/essays/SatyaEssay.html | archivedate = 11 November 2008 | df = dmy-all }}.</ref> This was an idea he took up from his interpretation of [[Antonio Gramsci]] and the [[Frankfurt School]] of [[Critical Theory]];<ref>{{Citation | first = Dietrich | last = Schwanitz | url = http://www.marcuse.org/herbert/booksabout/genlreviews/98RevKraushaarFkftSchStudentFAZ.htm | title = Frankfurter Schule und Studentenbewegung | newspaper = Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung | date = 29 June 1998 | publisher = Marcuse | language = German}}.</ref> accordingly, the quote is often wrongfully attributed to Gramsci.<ref>[[q:Antonio Gramsci]]</ref> In the 1970s he followed through on this idea by joining the nascent [[Green movement]].\n\n[[File:Dutschke-tomb.JPG|thumb|m|His grave in Berlin-Dahlem]]\nHe survived an [[assassination]] attempt by [[Josef Bachmann]] in 1968, but died 11 years later from a seizure brought on from brain damage sustained during the assassination attempt. Radical students blamed an anti-student campaign in the papers of the [[Axel Springer]] [[Axel Springer SE|publishing empire]] for the assassination attempt. This led to attempts to blockade the distribution of Springer newspapers all over Germany, which in turn led to major street battles in many German cities, considered the largest protests to that date in Germany.<ref>{{Citation | first = Paul | last = Hockenos | url = http://www.thenation.com/article/taz-year-thirty | title = ''Taz'' Year Thirty | newspaper = [[The Nation]] | date = 19 May 2008}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/einestages/rudi-dutschke-am-11-april-1968-schoss-ihn-ein-junger-nazi-nieder-a-1201324.html|title=Attentat vor 50 Jahren: Drei Kugeln auf Rudi Dutschke|last=Sontheimer|first=Michael|date=9 April 2018|work=Spiegel Online|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDutschke was born in [[Nuthe-Urstromtal|Sch\u00f6nefeld]] (present-day Nuthe-Urstromtal) near [[Luckenwalde]], [[Province of Brandenburg|Brandenburg]], the 4th son of a postal clerk. Raised in [[East Germany]] (GDR), he attended school and graduated from the ''[[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]]'' there. Interested in the ideas of [[religious socialism]], he was engaged in the youth organisation of the East German [[Evangelical Church in Germany|Evangelical Church]]. In 1956 he joined the socialist [[Free German Youth]] aiming at a sporting career as a [[Decathlon|decathlete]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hGIiAAAAMAAJ&q=dutschke+zehnkampf&dq=dutschke+zehnkampf&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjX_5vH7K3aAhXJfFAKHcCUDcUQ6AEIKjAA|title=Rudi Dutschke: mit Selbstzeugnissen und Bilddokumenten|last=Miermeister|first=J\u00fcrgen|date=1986|publisher=Rowohlt|isbn=9783499503498|language=de}}</ref>\n\nIn the same year he witnessed the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungarian Uprising]] and began to advocate the ideals of a [[democratic socialism]] beyond the official line of the [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|Socialist Unity Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbb-online.de/theodor/archiv/20170507_1832/dutschke.html|title=Wie Dutschkes Weltbild entstand|website=www.rbb-online.de|language=de|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/einestages/mythos-rudi-dutschke-a-946831.html|title=Mythos Rudi Dutschke: Der verhinderte Stadtguerillero|date=7 April 2008|work=Spiegel Online|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/article3822461/Dutschke-schrieb-ueber-seine-Angst-vor-der-Stasi.html|title=Studentenbewegung: Dutschke schrieb \u00fcber seine Angst vor der Stasi|last=WELT|date=28 May 2009|work=DIE WELT|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref> He obtained his ''[[Abitur]]'' degree in 1958 and completed an apprenticeship as an industrial clerk. As he refused to join the East Germany [[National People's Army]] and convinced many of his fellow students to refuse as well, he was prevented from attending university in the GDR.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-46225038.html|title=: \"WIR FORDERN DIE ENTEIGNUNG AXEL SPRINGERS\"|date=10 July 1967|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=9 April 2018|volume=29}}</ref> In August 1961, Dutschke [[Republikflucht|fled]] to the [[Marienfelde refugee transit camp|Marienfelde transit camp]] in [[West Berlin]], just three days before the [[Berlin Wall]] was built.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VEg-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT35&lpg=PT35&dq=dutschke+marienfelde&source=bl&ots=Bb5XnkzImj&sig=rBvh-vlcYBRR4HPO3Wg2HTVeOAw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwii8uTP663aAhWQXMAKHQtUDXsQ6AEIUzAF#v=onepage&q=dutschke%20marienfelde&f=false|title=Rudi Dutschke. Die Biographie|last=Chaussy|first=Ulrich|date=26 February 2018|publisher=Droemer eBook|isbn=9783426451410|language=de}}</ref>\n\nHe began to study [[sociology]], [[ethnology]], [[philosophy]] and history at the [[Free University of Berlin]] under [[Richard L\u00f6wenthal]] and [[Klaus Meschkat]] where he became acquainted with the [[existentialism|existentialist]] theories of [[Martin Heidegger]] and [[Jean-Paul Sartre]], and soon after also with alternative views of [[Marxism]] and the history of the [[labour movement]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Rudi Dutschke|last=Dutschke-Klotz|first=Gretchen|publisher=Kiepenheuer und Witsch|year=1996|isbn=978-3-462-02573-6|location=K\u00f6ln|pages=[https://archive.org/details/wirhatteneinbarb0000duts/page/38 38-,53-,172, 227, 459]|url=https://archive.org/details/wirhatteneinbarb0000duts/page/38}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/the-attack-on-rudi-dutschke-a-revolutionary-who-shaped-a-generation-a-546913.html|title=The Attack on Rudi Dutschke: A Revolutionary Who Shaped a Generation|date=11 April 2008|work=Spiegel Online|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref> Dutschke joined the German SDS ''[[Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund]]'' (which was not the same as the [[Students for a Democratic Society (1960 organization)|SDS]] in the US, but quite similar in goals) in 1965 and from that time on the SDS became the center of the student movement, growing very rapidly and organizing demonstrations against the war in [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1979/12/26/rudi-dutschke-39-led-german-student-revolt/fbab8efd-cbe4-4ef4-af0d-d2c2c2d93158/|title=Rudi Dutschke, 39, Led German Student Revolt|last=Hamill|first=Virginia|date=26 December 1979|work=Washington Post|access-date=9 April 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nHe married the American Gretchen Klotz ([[:de:Gretchen Dutschke-Klotz|de]]) in 1966. They had three children. Dutschke's third child, 1980-born Rudi-Marek Dutschke was born after his father's death. He is a politician of the [[Alliance '90/The Greens|German Green Party]]<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.kandidatenwatch.de/rudi_marek_dutschke-323-8572.html | title = Kandidatenwatch | place = DE | contribution = Rudi Marek Dutschke | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080929053604/http://www.kandidatenwatch.de/rudi_marek_dutschke-323-8572.html | archivedate = 29 September 2008 | df = dmy-all }}.</ref> as well as Dean's Office staffer of the [[Hertie School of Governance]]<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.hertie-school.org/team.php?nav_id=453 | title = Hertie-school}}.</ref> today. His older siblings are Hosea-Che Dutschke (named after the [[Old Testament]] [[minor prophet]] [[Hosea]] and [[Che Guevara]]) and their sister Polly-Nicole, both born in 1968.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n==Political views==\nInfluenced by critical theory, [[Rosa Luxemburg]], and critical Marxists and informed through his collaboration with fellow students from Africa and Latin America, Dutschke developed a theory and code of practice of social change via the practice of developing [[democracy]] in the process of revolutionizing society, collaborating with foreign students.<ref>{{Citation | first = Quinn | last = Slobodian | url = http://www.dukeupress.edu/Catalog/ViewProduct.php?productid=47580&viewby=subject&categoryid=100&sort=newest | title = Foreign Front: Third World Politics in Sixties West Germany | publisher = Duke University Press | chapter = 2 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130205231031/http://www.dukeupress.edu/Catalog/ViewProduct.php?productid=47580&viewby=subject&categoryid=100&sort=newest | archivedate = 5 February 2013 | df = dmy-all }}.</ref>\n\nDutschke also advocated that the transformation of Western societies should go hand in hand with [[Third World]] liberation movements and with democratization in communist countries of [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Eastern Europe]]. He was from a pious Lutheran family<ref>[https://books.google.com.au/books?id=mBjiBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT78&lpg=PT78&dq=rudi+dutschke+lutheran&source=bl&ots=_A87XUY8-w&sig=bzdMd_2XDtc5-EOgY5U7i-AnZYo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDMQ6AEwA2oVChMIx77Y7t-dxwIVh9QeCh1GdAkq#v=onepage&q=rudi%20dutschke%20lutheran&f=false]</ref> and his [[socialism]] had strongly [[Christianity|Christian]] roots; he called [[Jesus Christ]] the \"greatest revolutionary\", and in [[Easter]] 1963, he wrote that \"Jesus is risen. The decisive revolution in world history has happened \u2014 a revolution of all-conquering love. If people would fully receive this revealed love into their own existence, into the reality of the 'now', then the logic of insanity could no longer continue.\"<ref>{{Citation | first = Helmut | last = Frank | place = Bayern, DE | url = http://www.sonntagsblatt-bayern.de/03/2003_16_21_01.php?PHPSESSID=4c911... | contribution = Ich liebte diesen naiven Christen | title = Sonntagsblatt | date = 16\u201320 April 2003 | language = German | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110718060459/http://www.sonntagsblatt-bayern.de/03/2003_16_21_01.php?PHPSESSID=4c911... | archivedate = 18 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}.</ref>\n\n[[Benno Ohnesorg]]'s death in 1967 at the hands of German police pushed some in the student movement toward increasingly [[extremism|extremist]] violence and the formation of the [[Red Army Faction]]. The violence against Dutschke further [[radicalisation|radicalised]] parts of the student movement into committing several bombings and murders. Dutschke rejected this direction and feared that it would harm or cause the dissolution of the student movement. Instead he advocated a 'long march through the institutions' of power to create radical change from within government and society by becoming an integral part of the machinery.<ref name=\"Satya\" /> The meaning of Dutschke's idea of a '[[the long march through the institutions|long march through the institutions]]' is in fact highly contested: most historians of '68 in West Germany understand it to mean advocating setting up an alternative society and recreating the institutions which were seen by Dutschke as beyond reform in their current state. It is highly unlikely Dutschke would have promoted change from within the parliamentary and judicial system, which were populated by former Nazis and political conservatives.<ref>{{Citation | editor1-first = Belinda | editor1-last = Davis | editor2-first = Wilfried | editor2-last = Mausbach | editor3-first = Martin | editor3-last = Klimke | title = Changing the World, Changing Oneself: Political Protest and Collective Identities in West Germany and the U.S. in the 1960s and 1970s}}.</ref> This is made clear in the SDS reaction to the [[Kiesinger]]-led [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|CDU]]-[[SPD]] grand coalition and the authoritarian Emergency Laws they passed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-46209544.html|title=STUDENTEN / DUTSCHKE: Der lange Marsch|date=11 December 1967|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=9 April 2018|volume=51}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Gedenkplatte f\u00fcr Rudi Dutschke in Berlin-Wilmersdorf.JPG|thumb|Memorial plate for Rudi Dutschke at Kurf\u00fcrstendamm and Joachim-Friedrich Stra\u00dfe in [[Berlin]], Germany]]\n\n==Shooting and later life==\nOn 11 April 1968, Dutschke was shot in the head by a young anti-communist, [[Josef Bachmann]].<ref name=Burleigh230>{{Cite book |title=Blood and Rage: History of Terrorism |last=Burleigh |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Burleigh |year=2011 |publisher=HarperCollins |isbn= 9780062047175 |page=230 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6rlYvLTXcPAC&pg=PA230#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate= }}</ref> Dutschke survived the assassination attempt, and he and his family went to the United Kingdom in the hope that he could recuperate there. Dutschke and Bachmann shared correspondence over the next year, until Bachmann's suicide in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lieber Josef Bachmann: Diese Briefe schrieb Dutschke an seinen Attent\u00e4ter|url=http://www.bild.de/politik/2010/an-attentaeter-josef-bachmann-12348078.bild.html|website=Der Bild|date=27 April 2010|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref> Dutschke was accepted at [[Clare Hall, Cambridge|Clare Hall]], a graduate college at the [[University of Cambridge]], to finish his degree in 1969, but in 1971 the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government under [[Edward Heath]] expelled him and his family as an \"undesirable alien\" who had engaged in \"subversive activity\", causing a political storm in London. They then moved to [[Aarhus|\u00c5rhus]], Denmark, after professor [[Johannes Sl\u00f8k]] had offered him a job at the [[University of Aarhus]] which made it possible for Dutschke to gain a Danish residence permit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9081206.html|title=: \"Herz der Revolte\"|last=Halter|first=Hans|date=19 August 1996|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=9 April 2018|volume=34}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.au.dk/om/profil/historie/showroom/galleri/personer/rudidutschke19401979/|title=Rudi Dutschke (1940-1979)|last=6112@au.dk|date=15 February 2018|website=www.au.dk|language=da|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nDutschke re-entered the German political scene after protests against the building of [[nuclear power]] plants activated a new movement in the mid-1970s. He also began working with dissidents opposing the [[Communism|Communist]] governments in East Germany, Poland, Yugoslavia, Hungary, and Czechoslovakia, including [[Robert Havemann]], [[Wolf Biermann]], [[Milan Hor\u00e1\u010dek]], [[Adam Michnik]] and others.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Msswvx3VslIC&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=dutschke+horacek&source=bl&ots=PBTEGi_KDU&sig=9Lxpd9w5h2ID1woils1oMFxl404&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi4pfK89q3aAhWOWsAKHdjLDN0Q6AEIcTAK#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The German Greens: Paradox Between Movement and Party|last=Mayer|first=Margit|last2=Ely|first2=John|date=1998|publisher=Temple University Press|isbn=9781566395168|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MvK-o1OG5bUC&pg=PA364&dq=dutschke+havemann&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAl9jl9q3aAhXCbFAKHVusA6cQ6AEIXzAI#v=onepage&q=dutschke%20havemann&f=false|title=Volkserhebung gegen den SED-Staat: eine Bestandsaufnahme zum 17. Juni 1953|last=Engelmann|first=Roger|last2=Kowalczuk|first2=Ilko-Sascha|date=2005|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|isbn=9783525350041|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6BkhDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=dutschke+nuclear+power&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwit9NqZ-K3aAhUPa1AKHfGMBcMQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=dutschke%20nuclear%20power&f=false|title=Writing the Revolution: The Construction of \"1968\" in Germany|last=Cornils|first=Ingo|date=2016|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=9781571139542|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBecause of brain damage sustained in the assassination attempt, Dutschke continued to suffer health problems. He died on 24 December 1979 in \u00c5rhus. He had an [[epileptic seizure]] while in the bathtub and drowned.<ref name=Burleigh230/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/a-667960.html |title=Erinnerungen: Hosea Dutschke \u00fcber den Tod seines Vaters vor 30 Jahren |last=Wendland |first=Johannes |year=2009 |work=Spiegel Online |publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] |language=German |trans-title=Memories: Hosea Dutschke On His Father's Death 30 Years Ago |accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 it emerged that [[Rudolf Augstein]], publisher of ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', provided financial support to Dutschke so he could continue to work on his dissertations. Between 1970 and 1973 he paid 1,000 [[Deutsche Mark|German Marks]] per year. At the same time they started an exchange of letters in which they also discussed the student revolts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/1.5711015|title=Bislang unbekannte Akten: \"Spiegel\"-Gr\u00fcnder Augstein unterst\u00fctzte Dutschke finanziell|work=FAZ.NET|access-date=28 July 2018|language=de|issn=0174-4909}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{Citation | first = Rudi | last = Dutschke | title = Mein langer Marsch: Reden, Schriften und Tageb\u00fccher aus zwanzig Jahren | publisher = Rowohlt | place = Hamburg, DE | year = 1980 | language = German}}.\n* {{Citation | title = Jeder hat sein Leben ganz zu leben | type = diaries | first = Rudi | last = Dutschke | editor-first = Gretchen | editor-last = Dutschke | publisher = Kiepenheuer & Witsch | place = K\u00f6ln, DE | year = 2003 | ISBN = 3-462-03224-0 | language = German}} (1963\u20131979).\n* {{Citation | first = Rudi | last = Dutschke | title = It Is Not Easy to Walk Upright | journal = [[TELOS (journal)|TELOS]] | issue = 52 | date = Summer 1982 | place = New York | publisher = [[Telos Press]]}}.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Citation | first = Gretchen | last = Dutschke | title = Wir hatten ein barbarisches, sch\u00f6nes Leben | type = biography | publisher = Kiepenheuer & Witsch | place = K\u00f6ln, DE | year = 1996 | ISBN = 3-462-02573-2 | language = German | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/wirhatteneinbarb0000duts }}.\n* Michaela Karl: ''Rudi Dutschke \u2013 Revolution\u00e4r ohne Revolution.'' Neue Kritik, Frankfurt am Main 2003, {{ISBN|3-8015-0364-X}}.\n* Bernd Rabehl: ''Rudi Dutschke \u2013 Revolution\u00e4r im geteilten Deutschland.'' Edition Antaios, Dresden 2002, {{ISBN|3-935063-06-7}}.\n* Rudi-Marek Dutschke: ''Spuren meines Vaters.'' Kiepenheuer und Witsch, K\u00f6ln 2001, {{ISBN|3-462-03038-8}}.\n* Jutta Ditfurth: ''Rudi und Ulrike: Geschichte einer Freundschaft.'' Droemer Knaur, M\u00fcnchen 2008, {{ISBN|3-426-27456-6}}.\n* Tilman P. Fichter, Siegward L\u00f6nnendonker ''Dutschkes Deutschland. Der Sozialistische Deutsche Studentenbund, die nationale Frage und die DDR-Kritik von links.'' Klartext, Essen 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-8375-0481-1}}.\n* Willi Baer, Karl-Heinz Dellwo ''Rudi Dutschke \u2013 Aufrecht Gehen. 1968 und der libert\u00e4re Kommunismus,'' Laika, Hamburg 2012, {{ISBN|978-3-942281-81-2}}.\n* Carsten Prien: ''Dutschkismus - die politische Theorie Rudi Dutschkes'', Ousia Lesekreis Verlag, Seedorf 2015, {{ISBN|978-3-944570-58-7}}.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kommune 1]]\n* [[Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund]]\n* [[:de:Rudi Dutschke|Rudi Dutschke - German Wikipedia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Rudi Dutschke|Rudi Dutschke}}\n* {{IMDb name|0969057}}\n* {{DNB portal|118528327|TYP=}}\n* {{Citation | url = http://www.dhm.de/lemo/html/biografien/DutschkeRudi/ | type = biography | publisher = German Historic Museum | language = German | place = DE | title = Dutschke, Rudi}}.\n* {{Citation\n | last = Salvatore\n | first = Gaston\n | author-link = Gaston Salvatore\n | title = Lost in the Federal Republic, Scenes from Another Era\n | newspaper = Dossier 1968\n | pages =\n | year = 2008\n | date =\n | url = http://www.goethe.de/ges/pok/dos/dos/wdp/hel/en3160707.htm\n | accessdate = 11 November 2012 }}.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dutschke, Rudi}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dahme-Spreewald]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund members]]\n[[Category:German Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:German Marxists]]\n[[Category:People with epilepsy]]\n[[Category:Shooting survivors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from epilepsy]]\n[[Category:Lutheran socialists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare Hall, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Extraparliamentary Opposition]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Rudi Dutschke\n|image         = Rudi.jpg\n|image_size    =\n|alt           =\n|caption       =\n|birth_name    = Alfred Willi Rudi Dutschke\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date|1940|3|7|df=yes}}\n|birth_place   = [[Nuthe-Urstromtal|Sch\u00f6nefeld]], [[Gau March of Brandenburg|Brandenburg]], [[Germany]]\n|death_date    = {{Death date and age|1979|12|24|1940|3|7|df=yes}}\n|death_place   = [[\u00c5rhus]], Denmark\n|death_cause   = Drowning following [[epileptic seizure]]\n|known_for     = Spokesperson of the [[German student movement]]\n|alma_mater    = [[Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin]]\n|home_town     = [[Luckenwalde]], [[East Germany]]\n|spouse        = {{marriage|Gretchen Klotz|1966}}\n|children      = 3\n|footnotes     = }}\n'''Alfred Willi Rudolf \"Rudi\" Dutschke''' ({{IPA-de|\u02c8\u0281u\u02d0di \u02c8d\u028at\u0283k\u0259|lang}}; 7 March 1940 \u2013 24 December 1979) was a German Marxist [[Sociology|sociologist]] and a political activist in the [[German student movement]], and the [[Au\u00dferparlamentarische Opposition|APO]] of the 1960s. \n\nHe advocated a \"[[long march through the institutions]] of power\" to create radical change from within government and society by becoming an integral part of the machinery.<ref name=\"Satya\">{{Citation | first = Richard | last = Huffmann | url = http://www.baader-meinhof.com/essays/SatyaEssay.html | publisher = Baader Meinhof | contribution = The Limits of Violence | title = Satya | date = March 2004 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20081111192512/http://www.baader-meinhof.com/essays/SatyaEssay.html | archivedate = 11 November 2008 | df = dmy-all }}.</ref> This was an idea he took up from his interpretation of [[Antonio Gramsci]] and the [[Frankfurt School]] of [[Critical Theory]];<ref>{{Citation | first = Dietrich | last = Schwanitz | url = http://www.marcuse.org/herbert/booksabout/genlreviews/98RevKraushaarFkftSchStudentFAZ.htm | title = Frankfurter Schule und Studentenbewegung | newspaper = Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung | date = 29 June 1998 | publisher = Marcuse | language = German}}.</ref> accordingly, the quote is often wrongfully attributed to Gramsci.<ref>[[q:Antonio Gramsci]]</ref> In the 1970s he followed through on this idea by joining the nascent [[Green movement]].\n\n[[File:Dutschke-tomb.JPG|thumb|m|His grave in Berlin-Dahlem]]\nHe survived an [[assassination]] attempt by [[Josef Bachmann]] in 1968, but died 11 years later from a seizure brought on from brain damage sustained during the assassination attempt. Radical students blamed an anti-student campaign in the papers of the [[Axel Springer]] [[Axel Springer SE|publishing empire]] for the assassination attempt. This led to attempts to blockade the distribution of Springer newspapers all over Germany, which in turn led to major street battles in many German cities, considered the largest protests to that date in Germany.<ref>{{Citation | first = Paul | last = Hockenos | url = http://www.thenation.com/article/taz-year-thirty | title = ''Taz'' Year Thirty | newspaper = [[The Nation]] | date = 19 May 2008}}.</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/einestages/rudi-dutschke-am-11-april-1968-schoss-ihn-ein-junger-nazi-nieder-a-1201324.html|title=Attentat vor 50 Jahren: Drei Kugeln auf Rudi Dutschke|last=Sontheimer|first=Michael|date=9 April 2018|work=Spiegel Online|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nDutschke was born in [[Nuthe-Urstromtal|Sch\u00f6nefeld]] (present-day Nuthe-Urstromtal) near [[Luckenwalde]], [[Province of Brandenburg|Brandenburg]], the 4th son of a postal clerk. Raised in [[East Germany]] (GDR), he attended school and graduated from the ''[[Gymnasium (school)|Gymnasium]]'' there. Interested in the ideas of [[religious socialism]], he was engaged in the youth organisation of the East German [[Evangelical Church in Germany|Evangelical Church]]. In 1956 he joined the socialist [[Free German Youth]] aiming at a sporting career as a [[Decathlon|decathlete]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=hGIiAAAAMAAJ&q=dutschke+zehnkampf&dq=dutschke+zehnkampf&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjX_5vH7K3aAhXJfFAKHcCUDcUQ6AEIKjAA|title=Rudi Dutschke: mit Selbstzeugnissen und Bilddokumenten|last=Miermeister|first=J\u00fcrgen|date=1986|publisher=Rowohlt|isbn=9783499503498|language=de}}</ref>\n\nIn the same year he witnessed the [[Hungarian Revolution of 1956|Hungarian Uprising]] and began to advocate the ideals of a [[democratic socialism]] beyond the official line of the [[Socialist Unity Party of Germany|Socialist Unity Party]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rbb-online.de/theodor/archiv/20170507_1832/dutschke.html|title=Wie Dutschkes Weltbild entstand|website=www.rbb-online.de|language=de|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/einestages/mythos-rudi-dutschke-a-946831.html|title=Mythos Rudi Dutschke: Der verhinderte Stadtguerillero|date=7 April 2008|work=Spiegel Online|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.welt.de/politik/article3822461/Dutschke-schrieb-ueber-seine-Angst-vor-der-Stasi.html|title=Studentenbewegung: Dutschke schrieb \u00fcber seine Angst vor der Stasi|last=WELT|date=28 May 2009|work=DIE WELT|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref> He obtained his ''[[Abitur]]'' degree in 1958 and completed an apprenticeship as an industrial clerk. As he refused to join the East Germany [[National People's Army]] and convinced many of his fellow students to refuse as well, he was prevented from attending university in the GDR.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-46225038.html|title=: \"WIR FORDERN DIE ENTEIGNUNG AXEL SPRINGERS\"|date=10 July 1967|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=9 April 2018|volume=29}}</ref> In August 1961, Dutschke [[Republikflucht|fled]] to the [[Marienfelde refugee transit camp|Marienfelde transit camp]] in [[West Berlin]], just three days before the [[Berlin Wall]] was built.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=VEg-DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT35&lpg=PT35&dq=dutschke+marienfelde&source=bl&ots=Bb5XnkzImj&sig=rBvh-vlcYBRR4HPO3Wg2HTVeOAw&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwii8uTP663aAhWQXMAKHQtUDXsQ6AEIUzAF#v=onepage&q=dutschke%20marienfelde&f=false|title=Rudi Dutschke. Die Biographie|last=Chaussy|first=Ulrich|date=26 February 2018|publisher=Droemer eBook|isbn=9783426451410|language=de}}</ref>\n\nHe began to study [[sociology]], [[ethnology]], [[philosophy]] and history at the [[Free University of Berlin]] under [[Richard L\u00f6wenthal]] and [[Klaus Meschkat]] where he became acquainted with the [[existentialism|existentialist]] theories of [[Martin Heidegger]] and [[Jean-Paul Sartre]], and soon after also with alternative views of [[Marxism]] and the history of the [[labour movement]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|title=Rudi Dutschke|last=Dutschke-Klotz|first=Gretchen|publisher=Kiepenheuer und Witsch|year=1996|isbn=978-3-462-02573-6|location=K\u00f6ln|pages=[https://archive.org/details/wirhatteneinbarb0000duts/page/38 38-,53-,172, 227, 459]|url=https://archive.org/details/wirhatteneinbarb0000duts/page/38}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/the-attack-on-rudi-dutschke-a-revolutionary-who-shaped-a-generation-a-546913.html|title=The Attack on Rudi Dutschke: A Revolutionary Who Shaped a Generation|date=11 April 2008|work=Spiegel Online|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref> Dutschke joined the German SDS ''[[Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund]]'' (which was not the same as the [[Students for a Democratic Society (1960 organization)|SDS]] in the US, but quite similar in goals) in 1965 and from that time on the SDS became the center of the student movement, growing very rapidly and organizing demonstrations against the war in [[Vietnam]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/local/1979/12/26/rudi-dutschke-39-led-german-student-revolt/fbab8efd-cbe4-4ef4-af0d-d2c2c2d93158/|title=Rudi Dutschke, 39, Led German Student Revolt|last=Hamill|first=Virginia|date=26 December 1979|work=Washington Post|access-date=9 April 2018|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\nHe married the American Gretchen Klotz ([[:de:Gretchen Dutschke-Klotz|de]]) in 1966. They had three children. Dutschke's third child, 1980-born Rudi-Marek Dutschke was born after his father's death. He is a politician of the [[Alliance '90/The Greens|German Green Party]]<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.kandidatenwatch.de/rudi_marek_dutschke-323-8572.html | title = Kandidatenwatch | place = DE | contribution = Rudi Marek Dutschke | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080929053604/http://www.kandidatenwatch.de/rudi_marek_dutschke-323-8572.html | archivedate = 29 September 2008 | df = dmy-all }}.</ref> as well as Dean's Office staffer of the [[Hertie School of Governance]]<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.hertie-school.org/team.php?nav_id=453 | title = Hertie-school}}.</ref> today. His older siblings are Hosea-Che Dutschke (named after the [[Old Testament]] [[minor prophet]] [[Hosea]] and [[Che Guevara]]) and their sister Polly-Nicole, both born in 1968.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" />\n==Political views==\nInfluenced by critical theory, [[Rosa Luxemburg]], and critical Marxists and informed through his collaboration with fellow students from Africa and Latin America, Dutschke developed a theory and code of practice of social change via the practice of developing [[democracy]] in the process of revolutionizing society, collaborating with foreign students.<ref>{{Citation | first = Quinn | last = Slobodian | url = http://www.dukeupress.edu/Catalog/ViewProduct.php?productid=47580&viewby=subject&categoryid=100&sort=newest | title = Foreign Front: Third World Politics in Sixties West Germany | publisher = Duke University Press | chapter = 2 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130205231031/http://www.dukeupress.edu/Catalog/ViewProduct.php?productid=47580&viewby=subject&categoryid=100&sort=newest | archivedate = 5 February 2013 | df = dmy-all }}.</ref>\n\nDutschke also advocated that the transformation of Western societies should go hand in hand with [[Third World]] liberation movements and with democratization in communist countries of [[Central Europe|Central]] and [[Eastern Europe]]. He was from a pious Lutheran family<ref>[https://books.google.com.au/books?id=mBjiBwAAQBAJ&pg=PT78&lpg=PT78&dq=rudi+dutschke+lutheran&source=bl&ots=_A87XUY8-w&sig=bzdMd_2XDtc5-EOgY5U7i-AnZYo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDMQ6AEwA2oVChMIx77Y7t-dxwIVh9QeCh1GdAkq#v=onepage&q=rudi%20dutschke%20lutheran&f=false]</ref> and his [[socialism]] had strongly [[Christianity|Christian]] roots; he called [[Jesus Christ]] the \"greatest revolutionary\", and in [[Easter]] 1963, he wrote that \"Jesus is risen. The decisive revolution in world history has happened \u2014 a revolution of all-conquering love. If people would fully receive this revealed love into their own existence, into the reality of the 'now', then the logic of insanity could no longer continue.\"<ref>{{Citation | first = Helmut | last = Frank | place = Bayern, DE | url = http://www.sonntagsblatt-bayern.de/03/2003_16_21_01.php?PHPSESSID=4c911... | contribution = Ich liebte diesen naiven Christen | title = Sonntagsblatt | date = 16\u201320 April 2003 | language = German | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110718060459/http://www.sonntagsblatt-bayern.de/03/2003_16_21_01.php?PHPSESSID=4c911... | archivedate = 18 July 2011 | df = dmy-all }}.</ref>\n\n[[Benno Ohnesorg]]'s death in 1967 at the hands of German police pushed some in the student movement toward increasingly [[extremism|extremist]] violence and the formation of the [[Red Army Faction]]. The violence against Dutschke further [[radicalisation|radicalised]] parts of the student movement into committing several bombings and murders. Dutschke rejected this direction and feared that it would harm or cause the dissolution of the student movement. Instead he advocated a 'long march through the institutions' of power to create radical change from within government and society by becoming an integral part of the machinery.<ref name=\"Satya\" /> The meaning of Dutschke's idea of a '[[the long march through the institutions|long march through the institutions]]' is in fact highly contested: most historians of '68 in West Germany understand it to mean advocating setting up an alternative society and recreating the institutions which were seen by Dutschke as beyond reform in their current state. It is highly unlikely Dutschke would have promoted change from within the parliamentary and judicial system, which were populated by former Nazis and political conservatives.<ref>{{Citation | editor1-first = Belinda | editor1-last = Davis | editor2-first = Wilfried | editor2-last = Mausbach | editor3-first = Martin | editor3-last = Klimke | title = Changing the World, Changing Oneself: Political Protest and Collective Identities in West Germany and the U.S. in the 1960s and 1970s}}.</ref> This is made clear in the SDS reaction to the [[Kiesinger]]-led [[Christian Democratic Union (Germany)|CDU]]-[[SPD]] grand coalition and the authoritarian Emergency Laws they passed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-46209544.html|title=STUDENTEN / DUTSCHKE: Der lange Marsch|date=11 December 1967|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=9 April 2018|volume=51}}</ref>\n\n[[Image:Gedenkplatte f\u00fcr Rudi Dutschke in Berlin-Wilmersdorf.JPG|thumb|Memorial plate for Rudi Dutschke at Kurf\u00fcrstendamm and Joachim-Friedrich Stra\u00dfe in [[Berlin]], Germany]]\n\n==Shooting and later life==\nOn 11 April 1968, Dutschke was shot in the head by a young anti-communist, [[Josef Bachmann]].<ref name=Burleigh230>{{Cite book |title=Blood and Rage: History of Terrorism |last=Burleigh |first=Michael |authorlink=Michael Burleigh |year=2011 |publisher=HarperCollins |isbn= 9780062047175 |page=230 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6rlYvLTXcPAC&pg=PA230#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate= }}</ref> Dutschke survived the assassination attempt, and he and his family went to the United Kingdom in the hope that he could recuperate there. Dutschke and Bachmann shared correspondence over the next year, until Bachmann's suicide in 1970.<ref>{{cite web|title=Lieber Josef Bachmann: Diese Briefe schrieb Dutschke an seinen Attent\u00e4ter|url=http://www.bild.de/politik/2010/an-attentaeter-josef-bachmann-12348078.bild.html|website=Der Bild|date=27 April 2010|accessdate=20 February 2017}}</ref> Dutschke was accepted at [[Clare Hall, Cambridge|Clare Hall]], a graduate college at the [[University of Cambridge]], to finish his degree in 1969, but in 1971 the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] government under [[Edward Heath]] expelled him and his family as an \"undesirable alien\" who had engaged in \"subversive activity\", causing a political storm in London. They then moved to [[Aarhus|\u00c5rhus]], Denmark, after professor [[Johannes Sl\u00f8k]] had offered him a job at the [[University of Aarhus]] which made it possible for Dutschke to gain a Danish residence permit.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/print/d-9081206.html|title=: \"Herz der Revolte\"|last=Halter|first=Hans|date=19 August 1996|work=Der Spiegel|access-date=9 April 2018|volume=34}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.au.dk/om/profil/historie/showroom/galleri/personer/rudidutschke19401979/|title=Rudi Dutschke (1940-1979)|last=6112@au.dk|date=15 February 2018|website=www.au.dk|language=da|access-date=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\nDutschke re-entered the German political scene after protests against the building of [[nuclear power]] plants activated a new movement in the mid-1970s. He also began working with dissidents opposing the [[Communism|Communist]] governments in East Germany, Poland, Yugoslavia, Hungary, and Czechoslovakia, including [[Robert Havemann]], [[Wolf Biermann]], [[Milan Hor\u00e1\u010dek]], [[Adam Michnik]] and others.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Msswvx3VslIC&pg=PA35&lpg=PA35&dq=dutschke+horacek&source=bl&ots=PBTEGi_KDU&sig=9Lxpd9w5h2ID1woils1oMFxl404&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi4pfK89q3aAhWOWsAKHdjLDN0Q6AEIcTAK#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The German Greens: Paradox Between Movement and Party|last=Mayer|first=Margit|last2=Ely|first2=John|date=1998|publisher=Temple University Press|isbn=9781566395168|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=MvK-o1OG5bUC&pg=PA364&dq=dutschke+havemann&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiAl9jl9q3aAhXCbFAKHVusA6cQ6AEIXzAI#v=onepage&q=dutschke%20havemann&f=false|title=Volkserhebung gegen den SED-Staat: eine Bestandsaufnahme zum 17. Juni 1953|last=Engelmann|first=Roger|last2=Kowalczuk|first2=Ilko-Sascha|date=2005|publisher=Vandenhoeck & Ruprecht|isbn=9783525350041|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6BkhDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&dq=dutschke+nuclear+power&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwit9NqZ-K3aAhUPa1AKHfGMBcMQ6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=dutschke%20nuclear%20power&f=false|title=Writing the Revolution: The Construction of \"1968\" in Germany|last=Cornils|first=Ingo|date=2016|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=9781571139542|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBecause of brain damage sustained in the assassination attempt, Dutschke continued to suffer health problems. He died on 24 December 1979 in \u00c5rhus. He had an [[epileptic seizure]] while in the bathtub and drowned.<ref name=Burleigh230/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.spiegel.de/spiegel/a-667960.html |title=Erinnerungen: Hosea Dutschke \u00fcber den Tod seines Vaters vor 30 Jahren |last=Wendland |first=Johannes |year=2009 |work=Spiegel Online |publisher=[[Der Spiegel]] |language=German |trans-title=Memories: Hosea Dutschke On His Father's Death 30 Years Ago |accessdate=27 February 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018 it emerged that [[Rudolf Augstein]], publisher of ''[[Der Spiegel]]'', provided financial support to Dutschke so he could continue to work on his dissertations. Between 1970 and 1973 he paid 1,000 [[Deutsche Mark|German Marks]] per year. At the same time they started an exchange of letters in which they also discussed the student revolts.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.faz.net/1.5711015|title=Bislang unbekannte Akten: \"Spiegel\"-Gr\u00fcnder Augstein unterst\u00fctzte Dutschke finanziell|work=FAZ.NET|access-date=2018-07-28|language=de|issn=0174-4909}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{Citation | first = Rudi | last = Dutschke | title = Mein langer Marsch: Reden, Schriften und Tageb\u00fccher aus zwanzig Jahren | publisher = Rowohlt | place = Hamburg, DE | year = 1980 | language = German}}.\n* {{Citation | title = Jeder hat sein Leben ganz zu leben | type = diaries | first = Rudi | last = Dutschke | editor-first = Gretchen | editor-last = Dutschke | publisher = Kiepenheuer & Witsch | place = K\u00f6ln, DE | year = 2003 | ISBN = 3-462-03224-0 | language = German}} (1963\u20131979).\n* {{Citation | first = Rudi | last = Dutschke | title = It Is Not Easy to Walk Upright | journal = [[TELOS (journal)|TELOS]] | issue = 52 | date = Summer 1982 | place = New York | publisher = [[Telos Press]]}}.\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{Citation | first = Gretchen | last = Dutschke | title = Wir hatten ein barbarisches, sch\u00f6nes Leben | type = biography | publisher = Kiepenheuer & Witsch | place = K\u00f6ln, DE | year = 1996 | ISBN = 3-462-02573-2 | language = German | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/wirhatteneinbarb0000duts }}.\n* Michaela Karl: ''Rudi Dutschke \u2013 Revolution\u00e4r ohne Revolution.'' Neue Kritik, Frankfurt am Main 2003, {{ISBN|3-8015-0364-X}}.\n* Bernd Rabehl: ''Rudi Dutschke \u2013 Revolution\u00e4r im geteilten Deutschland.'' Edition Antaios, Dresden 2002, {{ISBN|3-935063-06-7}}.\n* Rudi-Marek Dutschke: ''Spuren meines Vaters.'' Kiepenheuer und Witsch, K\u00f6ln 2001, {{ISBN|3-462-03038-8}}.\n* Jutta Ditfurth: ''Rudi und Ulrike: Geschichte einer Freundschaft.'' Droemer Knaur, M\u00fcnchen 2008, {{ISBN|3-426-27456-6}}.\n* Tilman P. Fichter, Siegward L\u00f6nnendonker ''Dutschkes Deutschland. Der Sozialistische Deutsche Studentenbund, die nationale Frage und die DDR-Kritik von links.'' Klartext, Essen 2011, {{ISBN|978-3-8375-0481-1}}.\n* Willi Baer, Karl-Heinz Dellwo ''Rudi Dutschke \u2013 Aufrecht Gehen. 1968 und der libert\u00e4re Kommunismus,'' Laika, Hamburg 2012, {{ISBN|978-3-942281-81-2}}.\n* Carsten Prien: ''Dutschkismus - die politische Theorie Rudi Dutschkes'', Ousia Lesekreis Verlag, Seedorf 2015, {{ISBN|978-3-944570-58-7}}.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Kommune 1]]\n* [[Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund]]\n* [[:de:Rudi Dutschke|Rudi Dutschke - German Wikipedia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons|Rudi Dutschke|Rudi Dutschke}}\n* {{IMDb name|0969057}}\n* {{DNB portal|118528327|TYP=}}\n* {{Citation | url = http://www.dhm.de/lemo/html/biografien/DutschkeRudi/ | type = biography | publisher = German Historic Museum | language = German | place = DE | title = Dutschke, Rudi}}.\n* {{Citation\n | last = Salvatore\n | first = Gaston\n | author-link = Gaston Salvatore\n | title = Lost in the Federal Republic, Scenes from Another Era\n | newspaper = Dossier 1968\n | pages =\n | year = 2008\n | date =\n | url = http://www.goethe.de/ges/pok/dos/dos/wdp/hel/en3160707.htm\n | accessdate = 11 November 2012 }}.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dutschke, Rudi}}\n[[Category:1940 births]]\n[[Category:1979 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dahme-Spreewald]]\n[[Category:People from the Province of Brandenburg]]\n[[Category:Sozialistischer Deutscher Studentenbund members]]\n[[Category:German Christian socialists]]\n[[Category:German Marxists]]\n[[Category:People with epilepsy]]\n[[Category:Shooting survivors]]\n[[Category:Deaths from epilepsy]]\n[[Category:Lutheran socialists]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Clare Hall, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Extraparliamentary Opposition]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix overlinking.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rudi_Dutschke"}
